{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GsivLJk9hNLA39uKm9guob","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created. Per the user's instructions, I am NOT modifying `sprint-status.yaml` and NOT running git add/commit.\n\n**Story created:**\n\n- **Story ID:** 8.9\n- **Story Key:** 8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability\n- **File:** `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability.md`\n- **Status:** ready-for-dev\n\n**What it covers:**\n- 3 new Semgrep YAML rule files in `patches/observability/` targeting Rust `tracing` crate patterns\n- `rust-function-no-tracing.yaml` — functions without tracing instrumentation\n- `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` — error match arms without tracing\n- `rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml` — `.map_err()`/`.unwrap_or_else()` closures without tracing\n- No TypeScript code changes needed (Semgrep auto-discovers rules by `languages: [rust]`)\n- This is the final story in Epic 8 (Full Rust Stack Support)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- Workflow file was `.yaml` not `.md` — minor discovery mismatch from the skill's instructions which said to load `workflow.md`.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- None needed.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC2 (match arms with `Err`) and AC3 (`.map_err()`/`.unwrap_or_else()` closures) depend on Semgrep's Rust pattern matching capabilities. Semgrep's Rust support is generally good but pattern matching for match arms and closure bodies can be finicky — the dev agent should validate each rule with `semgrep --validate` and test against sample Rust code.\n- AC4 is tagged `integration-required` because verifying that `codeharness audit` correctly picks up Rust rules requires a real Rust project with Semgrep installed — not feasible in a unit test subprocess.\n- The existing `analyzer.ts` hardcodes rule name constants (`FUNCTION_NO_LOG_RULE`, `CATCH_WITHOUT_LOGGING_RULE`, `ERROR_PATH_NO_LOG_RULE`) for summary computation. The new Rust rules will have different IDs (`rust-function-no-tracing`, `rust-catch-without-tracing`, `rust-error-path-no-tracing`) which won't match those constants. This means `computeSummary()` won't count Rust gaps in `functionsWithoutLogs` or `errorHandlersWithoutLogs`. The gaps will still appear in the output but the summary percentages will be off for Rust projects. This is arguably a bug but is outside this story's scope — the epic ACs don't mention summary accuracy.\n\n**Observations:**\n- This is a pure-config story — no TypeScript changes, just 3 YAML files. Unusually clean scope.\n- The `.ts` files alongside the existing `.yaml` rules in `patches/observability/` appear to be TypeScript test wrappers — the story explicitly instructs the dev agent not to create analogous `.ts` files for Rust.\n- The `computeSummary()` rule-name mismatch noted above could be a good follow-up story if Rust audit accuracy matters."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a8b5a3cb1cf3e8c85 (use SendMessage with to: 'a8b5a3cb1cf3e8c85' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 53455\ntool_uses: 28\nduration_ms: 161642</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9d3ab825-6dfa-42d3-92d1-28b7bc09852d","uuid":"c51b4671-0be2-4d43-ab7e-f046bfbfee0f","timestamp":"2026-03-23T08:35:45.008Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-create-story for story 8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a8b5a3cb1cf3e8c85","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created. Per the user's instructions, I am NOT modifying `sprint-status.yaml` and NOT running git add/commit.\n\n**Story created:**\n\n- **Story ID:** 8.9\n- **Story Key:** 8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability\n- **File:** `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability.md`\n- **Status:** ready-for-dev\n\n**What it covers:**\n- 3 new Semgrep YAML rule files in `patches/observability/` targeting Rust `tracing` crate patterns\n- `rust-function-no-tracing.yaml` — functions without tracing instrumentation\n- `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` — error match arms without tracing\n- `rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml` — `.map_err()`/`.unwrap_or_else()` closures without tracing\n- No TypeScript code changes needed (Semgrep auto-discovers rules by `languages: [rust]`)\n- This is the final story in Epic 8 (Full Rust Stack Support)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- Workflow file was `.yaml` not `.md` — minor discovery mismatch from the skill's instructions which said to load `workflow.md`.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- None needed.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC2 (match arms with `Err`) and AC3 (`.map_err()`/`.unwrap_or_else()` closures) depend on Semgrep's Rust pattern matching capabilities. Semgrep's Rust support is generally good but pattern matching for match arms and closure bodies can be finicky — the dev agent should validate each rule with `semgrep --validate` and test against sample Rust code.\n- AC4 is tagged `integration-required` because verifying that `codeharness audit` correctly picks up Rust rules requires a real Rust project with Semgrep installed — not feasible in a unit test subprocess.\n- The existing `analyzer.ts` hardcodes rule name constants (`FUNCTION_NO_LOG_RULE`, `CATCH_WITHOUT_LOGGING_RULE`, `ERROR_PATH_NO_LOG_RULE`) for summary computation. The new Rust rules will have different IDs (`rust-function-no-tracing`, `rust-catch-without-tracing`, `rust-error-path-no-tracing`) which won't match those constants. This means `computeSummary()` won't count Rust gaps in `functionsWithoutLogs` or `errorHandlersWithoutLogs`. The gaps will still appear in the output but the summary percentages will be off for Rust projects. This is arguably a bug but is outside this story's scope — the epic ACs don't mention summary accuracy.\n\n**Observations:**\n- This is a pure-config story — no TypeScript changes, just 3 YAML files. Unusually clean scope.\n- The `.ts` files alongside the existing `.yaml` rules in `patches/observability/` appear to be TypeScript test wrappers — the story explicitly instructs the dev agent not to create analogous `.ts` files for Rust.\n- The `computeSummary()` rule-name mismatch noted above could be a good follow-up story if Rust audit accuracy matters."}],"totalDurationMs":161642,"totalTokens":53455,"totalToolUseCount":28,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3330,"cache_read_input_tokens":49324,"output_tokens":800,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3330},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
