{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0187Cpjy6rcUwwWZ8URPxtSa","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 8.9: Semgrep Rules for Rust Observability\n     2→\n     3→Status: ready-for-dev\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer auditing a Rust project,\n    10→I want Semgrep to detect functions and error paths without tracing,\n    11→so that observability gaps are identified automatically.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **AC1:** Given a Rust function without `tracing::debug!`, `tracing::info!`, or `#[instrument]`, when Semgrep runs with `rust-function-no-tracing` rule, then it reports an observability gap <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **AC2:** Given a Rust `match` arm handling `Err` without `tracing::error!` or `tracing::warn!`, when Semgrep runs with `rust-catch-without-tracing` rule, then it reports an observability gap <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **AC3:** Given a Rust `.map_err()` or `.unwrap_or_else()` closure without tracing macros, when Semgrep runs with `rust-error-path-no-tracing` rule, then it reports an observability gap <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **AC4:** Given all 3 Rust rule files in `patches/observability/`, when `codeharness audit` runs on a Rust project with Semgrep installed, then the observability static analysis dimension uses the Rust rules automatically (Semgrep auto-discovers by `languages: [rust]`) <!-- verification: integration-required -->\n    19→5. **AC5:** Given all changes, when `npm test` runs, then all existing tests pass with zero regressions and any new tests pass <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→\n    21→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    22→\n    23→- [ ] Task 1: Create `patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml` (AC: #1)\n    24→  - [ ] 1.1 Use existing `function-no-debug-log.yaml` as structural reference\n    25→  - [ ] 1.2 Match Rust `fn` declarations (plain `fn`, `pub fn`, `async fn`, `pub async fn`)\n    26→  - [ ] 1.3 Exclude functions containing `tracing::debug!(...)`, `tracing::info!(...)`, `tracing::warn!(...)`, `tracing::error!(...)`, `debug!(...)`, `info!(...)`, `warn!(...)`, `error!(...)` (bare macro imports)\n    27→  - [ ] 1.4 Exclude functions annotated with `#[tracing::instrument]` or `#[instrument]`\n    28→  - [ ] 1.5 Set `languages: [rust]`, severity `INFO`, metadata `category: observability`, `cwe: \"CWE-778: Insufficient Logging\"`\n    29→- [ ] Task 2: Create `patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` (AC: #2)\n    30→  - [ ] 2.1 Use existing `catch-without-logging.yaml` as structural reference\n    31→  - [ ] 2.2 Match Rust `match` arms with `Err($E)` patterns (e.g., `Err(e) => { ... }`, `Err(_) => { ... }`)\n    32→  - [ ] 2.3 Exclude arms containing `tracing::error!(...)`, `tracing::warn!(...)`, `error!(...)`, `warn!(...)` macros\n    33→  - [ ] 2.4 Set `languages: [rust]`, severity `WARNING`, same metadata as Task 1\n    34→- [ ] Task 3: Create `patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml` (AC: #3)\n    35→  - [ ] 3.1 Use existing `error-path-no-log.yaml` as structural reference\n    36→  - [ ] 3.2 Match `.map_err(|$E| { ... })` closures without tracing macros inside\n    37→  - [ ] 3.3 Match `.unwrap_or_else(|$E| { ... })` closures without tracing macros inside\n    38→  - [ ] 3.4 Set `languages: [rust]`, severity `WARNING`, same metadata\n    39→- [ ] Task 4: Validate rules with `semgrep --validate --config patches/observability/rust-*.yaml` (AC: #1, #2, #3)\n    40→- [ ] Task 5: Run full test suite — zero regressions (AC: #5)\n    41→\n    42→## Dev Notes\n    43→\n    44→### CRITICAL: No TypeScript Code Changes Required\n    45→\n    46→This story creates **only Semgrep YAML rule files**. No TypeScript source changes are needed. The analyzer module (`src/modules/observability/analyzer.ts`) already runs `semgrep scan --config patches/observability/ --json` against the project directory (line 80, 125). Semgrep auto-discovers rules by their `languages:` field, so adding `.yaml` files with `languages: [rust]` is sufficient — they will be used when scanning Rust projects and ignored for non-Rust projects.\n    47→\n    48→### Existing Rule Pattern (Follow Exactly)\n    49→\n    50→All 3 existing JS/TS rules share this YAML structure:\n    51→\n    52→```yaml\n    53→rules:\n    54→  - id: <rule-id>\n    55→    patterns:\n    56→      - pattern-either:    # Match target code patterns\n    57→          - pattern: |\n    58→              <code-pattern>\n    59→      - pattern-not: |     # Exclude when observability is present\n    60→          <code-with-logging>\n    61→    message: \"<description> — observability gap\"\n    62→    languages: [rust]      # CHANGED from [typescript, javascript]\n    63→    severity: INFO|WARNING\n    64→    metadata:\n    65→      category: observability\n    66→      cwe: \"CWE-778: Insufficient Logging\"\n    67→```\n    68→\n    69→### Rust Tracing Crate Patterns\n    70→\n    71→The Rust ecosystem uses the `tracing` crate (standard). Macros to detect as \"has observability\":\n    72→\n    73→- **Namespaced**: `tracing::debug!(...)`, `tracing::info!(...)`, `tracing::warn!(...)`, `tracing::error!(...)`, `tracing::trace!(...)`\n    74→- **Bare imports** (via `use tracing::*`): `debug!(...)`, `info!(...)`, `warn!(...)`, `error!(...)`, `trace!(...)`\n    75→- **Attribute**: `#[tracing::instrument]`, `#[instrument]`\n    76→\n    77→The epic scope states: \"Semgrep Rust rules target standard `tracing` crate patterns only (custom macros out of scope)\".\n    78→\n    79→### Semgrep Rust Pattern Syntax Notes\n    80→\n    81→Semgrep supports Rust natively. Key patterns:\n    82→\n    83→- `fn $FUNC(...) { ... }` matches any function\n    84→- `pub fn $FUNC(...) { ... }` matches public functions\n    85→- `async fn $FUNC(...) { ... }` matches async functions\n    86→- `#[$ATTR] fn $FUNC(...) { ... }` matches attributed functions\n    87→- `Err($E) => { ... }` matches error match arms\n    88→- `$X.map_err(|$E| { ... })` matches map_err closures\n    89→- `$X.unwrap_or_else(|$E| { ... })` matches unwrap_or_else closures\n    90→\n    91→Use `pattern-either` to combine multiple function forms. Use `pattern-not` and `pattern-not-inside` to exclude functions that already have tracing.\n    92→\n    93→### Semgrep Rule Validation\n    94→\n    95→After creating each rule file, validate syntax with:\n    96→```bash\n    97→semgrep --validate --config patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n    98→semgrep --validate --config patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n    99→semgrep --validate --config patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n   100→```\n   101→\n   102→You can also test rules against sample Rust code:\n   103→```bash\n   104→echo 'fn foo() { let x = 1; }' > /tmp/test.rs\n   105→semgrep scan --config patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/test.rs\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→### Architecture Constraints\n   109→\n   110→- **NFR1**: No file exceeds 300 lines — YAML rules are typically 30-115 lines, well within limit\n   111→- **NFR2**: All new code has unit tests, 0 regressions — the rules themselves are validated by `semgrep --validate`; the analyzer module tests already cover Semgrep integration\n   112→- **NFR3**: No new npm dependencies — these are YAML config files, no dependencies\n   113→- **Epic scope**: \"Semgrep Rust rules target standard `tracing` crate patterns only (custom macros out of scope)\"\n   114→\n   115→### File Structure\n   116→\n   117→Files to CREATE:\n   118→- `patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml` — Detects Rust functions without tracing instrumentation\n   119→- `patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` — Detects Rust error match arms without tracing\n   120→- `patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml` — Detects Rust error-path closures without tracing\n   121→\n   122→Files for REFERENCE only (do NOT modify):\n   123→- `patches/observability/function-no-debug-log.yaml` — JS/TS equivalent, structural template\n   124→- `patches/observability/catch-without-logging.yaml` — JS/TS equivalent, structural template\n   125→- `patches/observability/error-path-no-log.yaml` — JS/TS equivalent, structural template\n   126→- `src/modules/observability/analyzer.ts` — Runs Semgrep, no changes needed\n   127→\n   128→### Do NOT Create or Modify\n   129→\n   130→- Do NOT modify `analyzer.ts` — Semgrep auto-discovers rules by language\n   131→- Do NOT modify `dimensions.ts` — audit already calls `analyze()` which runs all rules\n   132→- Do NOT add TypeScript wrapper files for the Rust rules (existing `.ts` wrappers in `patches/observability/` are for JS/TS testing only)\n   133→- Do NOT create test fixtures with actual Rust projects — use `semgrep --validate` for rule validation\n   134→- Do NOT target `log` crate, `println!`, or custom macros — only `tracing` crate per epic scope\n   135→\n   136→### Project Structure Notes\n   137→\n   138→- All observability Semgrep rules live in `patches/observability/`\n   139→- Rule naming convention: `<language>-<pattern-name>.yaml` (new: `rust-` prefix)\n   140→- Existing rules: `function-no-debug-log.yaml`, `catch-without-logging.yaml`, `error-path-no-log.yaml` (JS/TS)\n   141→- The `.ts` files in `patches/observability/` are TypeScript wrappers for test purposes — do NOT create `.ts` wrappers for Rust rules\n   142→\n   143→### References\n   144→\n   145→- [Source: patches/observability/function-no-debug-log.yaml — existing JS/TS rule, structural template]\n   146→- [Source: patches/observability/catch-without-logging.yaml — existing JS/TS rule, structural template]\n   147→- [Source: patches/observability/error-path-no-log.yaml — existing JS/TS rule, structural template]\n   148→- [Source: src/modules/observability/analyzer.ts — analyzer module, runs Semgrep with auto-discovery]\n   149→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-rust-stack-support.md#Story8-9 — epic definition]\n   150→\n   151→### Previous Story Intelligence (8-8)\n   152→\n   153→- 8-8 added Cargo.toml parsing to `getProjectName()` in `src/modules/infra/docs-scaffold.ts` — no file overlap\n   154→- 8-8 confirmed all tests pass with zero regressions (3018 vitest tests, 307 BATS tests)\n   155→- This story touches ONLY `patches/observability/` — clean isolation from all previous stories\n   156→- All 8 prior Rust stories verified successfully; pattern: focused, isolated changes\n   157→\n   158→### Git Intelligence\n   159→\n   160→Recent commits: b1dd9c0 (8-8 verified), 2a601a7 (8-7 verified), f33294b (8-6 verified), 79f3449 (8-5 verified), 4e805b9 (8-4 verified).\n   161→All previous Rust stories verified successfully. This is the final story in Epic 8.\n   162→\n   163→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   164→## Verification Requirements\n   165→\n   166→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability.proof.md`)\n   167→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   168→- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100%)\n   169→\n   170→## Documentation Requirements\n   171→\n   172→- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (list modules touched)\n   173→- [ ] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability.md`\n   174→\n   175→## Testing Requirements\n   176→\n   177→- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   178→- [ ] Integration tests for cross-module interactions\n   179→- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n   180→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   181→\n   182→## Dev Agent Record\n   183→\n   184→### Agent Model Used\n   185→\n   186→Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context)\n   187→\n   188→### Debug Log References\n   189→\n   190→### Completion Notes List\n   191→\n   192→### File List\n   193→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Y5Vmp4wHswe3FNr3ap85bX","session_id":"9d3ab825-6dfa-42d3-92d1-28b7bc09852d","uuid":"ddf24493-14d4-466a-979c-63fe4e4ead93","timestamp":"2026-03-23T08:36:12.343Z"}
