{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012dNFoninDySU5y6TMhcr99","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Verification Proof: Story 8.9 — Semgrep Rules for Rust Observability\n     2→\n     3→**Verifier:** Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context) — Black-box verification\n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-23\n     5→**Container:** codeharness-verify (Semgrep 1.156.0, codeharness 0.23.1)\n     6→\n     7→## AC1: rust-function-no-tracing rule detects functions without tracing\n     8→\n     9→### Rule Validation\n    10→\n    11→```bash\n    12→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n    13→```\n    14→\n    15→```output\n    16→Configuration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→### Positive Cases (should detect)\n    20→\n    21→```bash\n    22→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n    23→```\n    24→\n    25→```output\n    26→Scanning 1 file tracked by git with 1 Code rule:\n    27→Scanning 1 file.\n    28→\n    29→Scan Summary\n    30→Scan completed successfully.\n    31→ Findings: 4 (4 blocking)\n    32→ Rules run: 1\n    33→ Targets scanned: 1\n    34→\n    35→4 Code Findings:\n    36→  rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n    37→    line 4: fn process_data(input: &str) -> String { ... }\n    38→    line 9: pub fn handle_request(req: Request) -> Response { ... }\n    39→    line 15: async fn fetch_data(url: &str) -> Result<String, Error> { ... }\n    40→    line 21: pub async fn serve(addr: &str) -> Result<(), Error> { ... }\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Negative Cases (should NOT detect)\n    44→\n    45→```bash\n    46→docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cat > /tmp/test_ac1_negative.rs << \"EOF\"\n    47→use tracing::{info, debug};\n    48→\n    49→#[instrument]\n    50→fn instrumented_function() {\n    51→    let x = 1;\n    52→}\n    53→\n    54→fn function_with_tracing() {\n    55→    tracing::info!(\"doing something\");\n    56→    let y = 2;\n    57→}\n    58→\n    59→fn function_with_bare_debug() {\n    60→    debug!(\"bare import debug\");\n    61→}\n    62→EOF'\n    63→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/test_ac1_negative.rs\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→```output\n    67→Scan completed successfully.\n    68→ Findings: 0 (0 blocking)\n    69→ Rules run: 1\n    70→ Targets scanned: 1\n    71→Ran 1 rule on 1 file: 0 findings.\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→### Fixture Coverage\n    75→\n    76→The fixture file contains 4 positive cases (plain fn, pub fn, async fn, pub async fn) and 12 negative cases (tracing::debug/info/warn/error, bare debug/info/error, tracing::trace namespaced/bare, #[tracing::instrument], #[instrument] on all fn forms). All 4 positive cases detected, all 12 negative cases correctly excluded.\n    77→\n    78→**Result: PASS**\n    79→\n    80→---\n    81→\n    82→## AC2: rust-catch-without-tracing rule detects Err match arms without tracing\n    83→\n    84→### Rule Validation\n    85→\n    86→```bash\n    87→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n    88→```\n    89→\n    90→```output\n    91→Configuration is invalid - found 1 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n    92→[ERROR] Pattern parse error in rule rust-catch-without-tracing:\n    93→ Invalid pattern for Rust:\n    94→--- pattern ---\n    95→Err($E) => { ... }\n    96→--- end pattern ---\n    97→Pattern error: Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error\n    98→```\n    99→\n   100→### Scan Attempt\n   101→\n   102→```bash\n   103→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.rs\n   104→```\n   105→\n   106→```output\n   107→[ERROR] Rule parse error in rule rust-catch-without-tracing:\n   108→ Invalid pattern for Rust: Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error\n   109→----- pattern -----\n   110→Err($E) => { ... }\n   111→----- end pattern -----\n   112→\n   113→Scan completed successfully.\n   114→ Findings: 0 (0 blocking)\n   115→ Rules run: 1\n   116→ Targets scanned: 1\n   117→Ran 1 rule on 1 file: 0 findings.\n   118→```\n   119→\n   120→### Analysis\n   121→\n   122→The pattern `Err($E) => { ... }` is not valid Rust syntax in Semgrep's parser. Match arms are not standalone expressions — they exist within a `match` block. Semgrep cannot parse this pattern for Rust, so the rule produces zero findings. The rule was validated only via unit tests (YAML parsing) during development, not with actual Semgrep execution (dev notes mention \"semgrep-core 1.136.0 Bigarray crash on macOS\").\n   123→\n   124→**Result: FAIL — Rule has invalid Rust pattern syntax. Semgrep cannot parse `Err($E) => { ... }` and produces zero findings.**\n   125→\n   126→---\n   127→\n   128→## AC3: rust-error-path-no-tracing rule detects map_err/unwrap_or_else without tracing\n   129→\n   130→### Rule Validation\n   131→\n   132→```bash\n   133→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n   134→```\n   135→\n   136→```output\n   137→Configuration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n   138→```\n   139→\n   140→### Positive Cases (should detect)\n   141→\n   142→```bash\n   143→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.rs\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→```output\n   147→Scanning 1 file tracked by git with 1 Code rule:\n   148→Scanning 1 file.\n   149→\n   150→Scan completed successfully.\n   151→ Findings: 2 (2 blocking)\n   152→ Rules run: 1\n   153→ Targets scanned: 1\n   154→\n   155→2 Code Findings:\n   156→  rust-error-path-no-tracing.rs\n   157→    line 5: let result = some_operation().map_err(|e| { CustomError::new(e) });\n   158→    line 12: let value = some_operation().unwrap_or_else(|e| { default_value() });\n   159→```\n   160→\n   161→### Negative Cases (fixture includes 8 traced variants)\n   162→\n   163→The fixture file contains 8 negative cases: map_err and unwrap_or_else with tracing::error!, tracing::warn!, bare error!, and bare warn!. All were correctly excluded (0 false positives from those 8 cases).\n   164→\n   165→**Result: PASS**\n   166→\n   167→---\n   168→\n   169→## AC4: Semgrep auto-discovers Rust rules when scanning Rust files\n   170→\n   171→### Auto-Discovery Test\n   172→\n   173→```bash\n   174→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/ /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n   175→```\n   176→\n   177→```output\n   178→Scanning 1 file tracked by git with 6 Code rules:\n   179→Scanning 1 file with 3 rust rules.\n   180→\n   181→Scan completed successfully.\n   182→ Findings: 4 (4 blocking)\n   183→ Rules run: 3\n   184→ Targets scanned: 1\n   185→Ran 3 rules on 1 file: 4 findings.\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→### Analysis\n   189→\n   190→Semgrep loaded all 6 rules from the observability directory (3 JS/TS + 3 Rust) and correctly filtered to only the 3 Rust rules when scanning a `.rs` file. The JS/TS rules were automatically excluded based on the `languages:` field. This confirms auto-discovery works as designed.\n   191→\n   192→Note: One of the 3 Rust rules (rust-catch-without-tracing) has a parse error and produces no findings, but auto-discovery itself functions correctly.\n   193→\n   194→**Result: PASS (with caveat — AC2 rule parse error means only 2 of 3 Rust rules actually function)**\n   195→\n   196→---\n   197→\n   198→## AC5: All existing tests pass with zero regressions\n   199→\n   200→### CLI Functionality\n   201→\n   202→```bash\n   203→docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n   204→```\n   205→\n   206→```output\n   207→0.23.1\n   208→```\n   209→\n   210→```bash\n   211→docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --help\n   212→```\n   213→\n   214→```output\n   215→Usage: codeharness [options] [command]\n   216→Makes autonomous coding agents produce software that actually works\n   217→Commands: init, bridge, run, verify, status, onboard, teardown, sync, coverage, doc-health, stack, query, retro-import, github-import\n   218→```\n   219→\n   220→### Test Suite\n   221→\n   222→```bash\n   223→docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cd /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness && npx vitest run --reporter=verbose 2>&1 | tail -10'\n   224→```\n   225→\n   226→```output\n   227→No test files found, exiting with code 1\n   228→```\n   229→\n   230→Test files are not shipped in the npm package (standard practice — tests are dev dependencies). The dev agent's completion notes report 3069 vitest tests passing across 114 files with zero regressions.\n   231→\n   232→### Package Integrity\n   233→\n   234→```bash\n   235→docker exec codeharness-verify ls /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/\n   236→```\n   237→\n   238→```output\n   239→AGENTS.md\n   240→__tests__\n   241→catch-without-logging.ts\n   242→catch-without-logging.yaml\n   243→error-path-no-log.ts\n   244→error-path-no-log.yaml\n   245→function-no-debug-log.ts\n   246→function-no-debug-log.yaml\n   247→rust-catch-without-tracing.rs\n   248→rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n   249→rust-error-path-no-tracing.rs\n   250→rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n   251→rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n   252→rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n   253→```\n   254→\n   255→All 3 Rust YAML rule files and 3 Rust fixture files are present. The CLI loads and runs correctly. Rule validation passes for 2 of 3 rules.\n   256→\n   257→**Result: PARTIAL PASS — Package is functional and CLI works. Cannot run test suite in container (tests not shipped). 2 of 3 new rules validate correctly; 1 rule (AC2) has a parse error.**\n   258→\n   259→---\n   260→\n   261→## Summary\n   262→\n   263→| AC | Description | Result |\n   264→|----|-------------|--------|\n   265→| AC1 | rust-function-no-tracing detects untraced functions | **PASS** |\n   266→| AC2 | rust-catch-without-tracing detects untraced Err arms | **FAIL** |\n   267→| AC3 | rust-error-path-no-tracing detects untraced error paths | **PASS** |\n   268→| AC4 | Auto-discovery uses Rust rules on Rust files | **PASS** (with AC2 caveat) |\n   269→| AC5 | All tests pass, zero regressions | **PARTIAL PASS** (cannot run tests in container; CLI functional) |\n   270→\n   271→## Overall Verdict: FAIL\n   272→\n   273→**AC2 is a blocking failure.** The `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` rule uses the pattern `Err($E) => { ... }` which is not valid Rust syntax for Semgrep's parser (Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error). The rule validates at the YAML level but fails at the Semgrep pattern parsing level, producing zero findings on any input. This was not caught during development because the dev agent could not run Semgrep locally (macOS Bigarray crash) and relied solely on YAML-parsing unit tests.\n   274→\n   275→AC1 and AC3 work correctly with proper positive/negative case coverage. AC4 auto-discovery functions as designed. AC5 cannot be fully verified in the container but the CLI is operational.\n   276→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9d3ab825-6dfa-42d3-92d1-28b7bc09852d","uuid":"fae434b0-0973-4ca6-ae11-f2dbf2851c34","timestamp":"2026-03-23T08:53:57.666Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/verification/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability-proof.md","content":"# Verification Proof: Story 8.9 — Semgrep Rules for Rust Observability\n\n**Verifier:** Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context) — Black-box verification\n**Date:** 2026-03-23\n**Container:** codeharness-verify (Semgrep 1.156.0, codeharness 0.23.1)\n\n## AC1: rust-function-no-tracing rule detects functions without tracing\n\n### Rule Validation\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n```\n\n```output\nConfiguration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n```\n\n### Positive Cases (should detect)\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n```\n\n```output\nScanning 1 file tracked by git with 1 Code rule:\nScanning 1 file.\n\nScan Summary\nScan completed successfully.\n Findings: 4 (4 blocking)\n Rules run: 1\n Targets scanned: 1\n\n4 Code Findings:\n  rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n    line 4: fn process_data(input: &str) -> String { ... }\n    line 9: pub fn handle_request(req: Request) -> Response { ... }\n    line 15: async fn fetch_data(url: &str) -> Result<String, Error> { ... }\n    line 21: pub async fn serve(addr: &str) -> Result<(), Error> { ... }\n```\n\n### Negative Cases (should NOT detect)\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cat > /tmp/test_ac1_negative.rs << \"EOF\"\nuse tracing::{info, debug};\n\n#[instrument]\nfn instrumented_function() {\n    let x = 1;\n}\n\nfn function_with_tracing() {\n    tracing::info!(\"doing something\");\n    let y = 2;\n}\n\nfn function_with_bare_debug() {\n    debug!(\"bare import debug\");\n}\nEOF'\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/test_ac1_negative.rs\n```\n\n```output\nScan completed successfully.\n Findings: 0 (0 blocking)\n Rules run: 1\n Targets scanned: 1\nRan 1 rule on 1 file: 0 findings.\n```\n\n### Fixture Coverage\n\nThe fixture file contains 4 positive cases (plain fn, pub fn, async fn, pub async fn) and 12 negative cases (tracing::debug/info/warn/error, bare debug/info/error, tracing::trace namespaced/bare, #[tracing::instrument], #[instrument] on all fn forms). All 4 positive cases detected, all 12 negative cases correctly excluded.\n\n**Result: PASS**\n\n---\n\n## AC2: rust-catch-without-tracing rule detects Err match arms without tracing\n\n### Rule Validation\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n```\n\n```output\nConfiguration is invalid - found 1 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n[ERROR] Pattern parse error in rule rust-catch-without-tracing:\n Invalid pattern for Rust:\n--- pattern ---\nErr($E) => { ... }\n--- end pattern ---\nPattern error: Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error\n```\n\n### Scan Attempt\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.rs\n```\n\n```output\n[ERROR] Rule parse error in rule rust-catch-without-tracing:\n Invalid pattern for Rust: Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error\n----- pattern -----\nErr($E) => { ... }\n----- end pattern -----\n\nScan completed successfully.\n Findings: 0 (0 blocking)\n Rules run: 1\n Targets scanned: 1\nRan 1 rule on 1 file: 0 findings.\n```\n\n### Analysis\n\nThe pattern `Err($E) => { ... }` is not valid Rust syntax in Semgrep's parser. Match arms are not standalone expressions — they exist within a `match` block. Semgrep cannot parse this pattern for Rust, so the rule produces zero findings. The rule was validated only via unit tests (YAML parsing) during development, not with actual Semgrep execution (dev notes mention \"semgrep-core 1.136.0 Bigarray crash on macOS\").\n\n**Result: FAIL — Rule has invalid Rust pattern syntax. Semgrep cannot parse `Err($E) => { ... }` and produces zero findings.**\n\n---\n\n## AC3: rust-error-path-no-tracing rule detects map_err/unwrap_or_else without tracing\n\n### Rule Validation\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n```\n\n```output\nConfiguration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n```\n\n### Positive Cases (should detect)\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.rs\n```\n\n```output\nScanning 1 file tracked by git with 1 Code rule:\nScanning 1 file.\n\nScan completed successfully.\n Findings: 2 (2 blocking)\n Rules run: 1\n Targets scanned: 1\n\n2 Code Findings:\n  rust-error-path-no-tracing.rs\n    line 5: let result = some_operation().map_err(|e| { CustomError::new(e) });\n    line 12: let value = some_operation().unwrap_or_else(|e| { default_value() });\n```\n\n### Negative Cases (fixture includes 8 traced variants)\n\nThe fixture file contains 8 negative cases: map_err and unwrap_or_else with tracing::error!, tracing::warn!, bare error!, and bare warn!. All were correctly excluded (0 false positives from those 8 cases).\n\n**Result: PASS**\n\n---\n\n## AC4: Semgrep auto-discovers Rust rules when scanning Rust files\n\n### Auto-Discovery Test\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep scan --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/ /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.rs\n```\n\n```output\nScanning 1 file tracked by git with 6 Code rules:\nScanning 1 file with 3 rust rules.\n\nScan completed successfully.\n Findings: 4 (4 blocking)\n Rules run: 3\n Targets scanned: 1\nRan 3 rules on 1 file: 4 findings.\n```\n\n### Analysis\n\nSemgrep loaded all 6 rules from the observability directory (3 JS/TS + 3 Rust) and correctly filtered to only the 3 Rust rules when scanning a `.rs` file. The JS/TS rules were automatically excluded based on the `languages:` field. This confirms auto-discovery works as designed.\n\nNote: One of the 3 Rust rules (rust-catch-without-tracing) has a parse error and produces no findings, but auto-discovery itself functions correctly.\n\n**Result: PASS (with caveat — AC2 rule parse error means only 2 of 3 Rust rules actually function)**\n\n---\n\n## AC5: All existing tests pass with zero regressions\n\n### CLI Functionality\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n```\n\n```output\n0.23.1\n```\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --help\n```\n\n```output\nUsage: codeharness [options] [command]\nMakes autonomous coding agents produce software that actually works\nCommands: init, bridge, run, verify, status, onboard, teardown, sync, coverage, doc-health, stack, query, retro-import, github-import\n```\n\n### Test Suite\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cd /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness && npx vitest run --reporter=verbose 2>&1 | tail -10'\n```\n\n```output\nNo test files found, exiting with code 1\n```\n\nTest files are not shipped in the npm package (standard practice — tests are dev dependencies). The dev agent's completion notes report 3069 vitest tests passing across 114 files with zero regressions.\n\n### Package Integrity\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify ls /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/\n```\n\n```output\nAGENTS.md\n__tests__\ncatch-without-logging.ts\ncatch-without-logging.yaml\nerror-path-no-log.ts\nerror-path-no-log.yaml\nfunction-no-debug-log.ts\nfunction-no-debug-log.yaml\nrust-catch-without-tracing.rs\nrust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\nrust-error-path-no-tracing.rs\nrust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\nrust-function-no-tracing.rs\nrust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n```\n\nAll 3 Rust YAML rule files and 3 Rust fixture files are present. The CLI loads and runs correctly. Rule validation passes for 2 of 3 rules.\n\n**Result: PARTIAL PASS — Package is functional and CLI works. Cannot run test suite in container (tests not shipped). 2 of 3 new rules validate correctly; 1 rule (AC2) has a parse error.**\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| AC | Description | Result |\n|----|-------------|--------|\n| AC1 | rust-function-no-tracing detects untraced functions | **PASS** |\n| AC2 | rust-catch-without-tracing detects untraced Err arms | **FAIL** |\n| AC3 | rust-error-path-no-tracing detects untraced error paths | **PASS** |\n| AC4 | Auto-discovery uses Rust rules on Rust files | **PASS** (with AC2 caveat) |\n| AC5 | All tests pass, zero regressions | **PARTIAL PASS** (cannot run tests in container; CLI functional) |\n\n## Overall Verdict: FAIL\n\n**AC2 is a blocking failure.** The `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` rule uses the pattern `Err($E) => { ... }` which is not valid Rust syntax for Semgrep's parser (Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error). The rule validates at the YAML level but fails at the Semgrep pattern parsing level, producing zero findings on any input. This was not caught during development because the dev agent could not run Semgrep locally (macOS Bigarray crash) and relied solely on YAML-parsing unit tests.\n\nAC1 and AC3 work correctly with proper positive/negative case coverage. AC4 auto-discovery functions as designed. AC5 cannot be fully verified in the container but the CLI is operational.\n","numLines":276,"startLine":1,"totalLines":276}}}
